WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.390 --> 00:00:03.060
- Some things are not normal.

00:00:03.060 --> 00:00:05.100
By that I mean if you go out in the world

00:00:05.100 --> 00:00:08.250
and start measuring things
like human height, IQ,

00:00:08.250 --> 00:00:10.410
or the size of apples on a tree.

00:00:10.410 --> 00:00:12.810
You will find that for
each of these things,

00:00:12.810 --> 00:00:16.410
most of the data clusters
around some average value.

00:00:16.410 --> 00:00:20.730
This is so common that we call
it the normal distribution,

00:00:20.730 --> 00:00:24.180
but some things in life are not like this.

00:00:24.180 --> 00:00:27.060
- Nature shows power
laws all over the place.

00:00:27.060 --> 00:00:28.050
That seems weird.

00:00:28.050 --> 00:00:30.750
Like, is nature tuning
itself to criticality?

00:00:30.750 --> 00:00:33.240
- If you make a crude measure
of how big is the world war

00:00:33.240 --> 00:00:34.890
by how many people it kills,

00:00:34.890 --> 00:00:37.110
you find that it follows a power law.

00:00:37.110 --> 00:00:42.110
The outcome will vary in size
over 10 million, 100 million.

00:00:42.270 --> 00:00:45.210
- It's much more likelihood
of really big events

00:00:45.210 --> 00:00:47.370
than you would expect from
a normal distribution,

00:00:47.370 --> 00:00:49.680
and they will totally skew the average.

00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:52.080
- The system you're
looking at doesn't have

00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:54.390
any inherent physical scale.

00:00:54.390 --> 00:00:56.250
It's really hard to know
what's gonna happen next.

00:00:56.250 --> 00:00:59.580
- The more you measure,
the bigger the average is,

00:00:59.580 --> 00:01:01.650
which is really weird,
it sounds impossible.

00:01:01.650 --> 00:01:04.530
- It's very important to try to understand

00:01:04.530 --> 00:01:06.090
which game you're playing

00:01:06.090 --> 00:01:09.153
and what are the payoffs
going to be in the long run.

00:01:10.590 --> 00:01:13.890
- In the late 1800s, Italian
engineer Vilfredo Pareto

00:01:13.890 --> 00:01:17.130
stumbled upon something
no one had seen before.

00:01:17.130 --> 00:01:19.860
See, he suspected there
might be a hidden pattern

00:01:19.860 --> 00:01:21.840
in how much money people make.

00:01:21.840 --> 00:01:23.520
So he gathered income tax records

00:01:23.520 --> 00:01:26.820
from Italy, England, France,
and other European countries,

00:01:26.820 --> 00:01:31.110
and for each country he plotted
the distribution of income.

00:01:31.110 --> 00:01:34.200
Each country he looked at,
he saw the same pattern,

00:01:34.200 --> 00:01:38.490
a pattern which still holds
in most countries to this day,

00:01:38.490 --> 00:01:41.370
and it's not a normal distribution.

00:01:41.370 --> 00:01:43.830
If you think about a normal
distribution like height,

00:01:43.830 --> 00:01:45.840
there's a clearly defined average

00:01:45.840 --> 00:01:48.900
and extreme outliers
basically never happen.

00:01:48.900 --> 00:01:50.640
I mean, you are never
going to find someone

00:01:50.640 --> 00:01:53.370
who is, say, five times
the average height,

00:01:53.370 --> 00:01:55.260
that would be physically impossible,

00:01:55.260 --> 00:01:57.990
but Pareto's income
distributions were different.

00:01:57.990 --> 00:01:59.520
Take this curve for England,

00:01:59.520 --> 00:02:00.900
it shows the number of people

00:02:00.900 --> 00:02:03.120
who earn more than a certain income.

00:02:03.120 --> 00:02:05.340
The curve starts off declining steeply,

00:02:05.340 --> 00:02:07.530
most people earn relatively little,

00:02:07.530 --> 00:02:09.690
but then it falls away gradually,

00:02:09.690 --> 00:02:12.600
much more slowly than a
normal distribution would,

00:02:12.600 --> 00:02:15.810
and it spans several orders of magnitude.

00:02:15.810 --> 00:02:18.270
There were people who
earned 5 times, 10 times,

00:02:18.270 --> 00:02:21.150
even 100 times more than others.

00:02:21.150 --> 00:02:22.830
That kind of spread just wouldn't happen

00:02:22.830 --> 00:02:24.633
if income were normally distributed.

00:02:25.800 --> 00:02:28.170
Now to shrink this huge spread of data,

00:02:28.170 --> 00:02:30.990
Pareto calculated the
logarithms of all the values

00:02:30.990 --> 00:02:32.760
and plotted those instead.

00:02:32.760 --> 00:02:35.340
In other words, he used a log-log plot,

00:02:35.340 --> 00:02:36.360
and when he did that,

00:02:36.360 --> 00:02:39.870
the broad curve transformed
into a straight line.

00:02:39.870 --> 00:02:42.810
The gradient was around negative 1.5.

00:02:42.810 --> 00:02:45.270
That means each time
you double the income,

00:02:45.270 --> 00:02:47.730
say, from 200 pounds to 400 pounds,

00:02:47.730 --> 00:02:50.160
the number of people
earning at least that amount

00:02:50.160 --> 00:02:53.580
drops off by a factor of
two to the power of 1.5,

00:02:53.580 --> 00:02:55.290
which is around 2.8.

00:02:55.290 --> 00:02:58.560
And this pattern holds for
every doubling of income.

00:02:58.560 --> 00:03:01.020
So Pareto could describe
the distribution of incomes

00:03:01.020 --> 00:03:02.940
with one simple equation.

00:03:02.940 --> 00:03:05.460
The number of people who
earn an income greater than

00:03:05.460 --> 00:03:08.520
or equal to X is
proportional to one over X

00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:09.573
to the power of 1.5.

00:03:10.830 --> 00:03:13.020
Now, that's what Pareto saw for England,

00:03:13.020 --> 00:03:16.230
but he performed the same
analysis on data from Italy,

00:03:16.230 --> 00:03:18.960
France, Prussia, and a
bunch of other countries,

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:22.410
and he saw the same thing again and again.

00:03:22.410 --> 00:03:26.010
Each time the data transformed
into a straight line

00:03:26.010 --> 00:03:28.650
and the gradients were remarkably similar.

00:03:28.650 --> 00:03:31.500
That meant Pareto could
describe the income distribution

00:03:31.500 --> 00:03:34.440
in each country with the same equation,

00:03:34.440 --> 00:03:37.140
one over the income to some power,

00:03:37.140 --> 00:03:39.930
where that power is just
the absolute gradient

00:03:39.930 --> 00:03:42.060
of the logarithmic graph.

00:03:42.060 --> 00:03:45.690
This type of relationship
is called a power law.

00:03:45.690 --> 00:03:48.120
When you move from the world
of normal distributions

00:03:48.120 --> 00:03:49.620
to the world of power laws,

00:03:49.620 --> 00:03:51.570
things change dramatically.

00:03:51.570 --> 00:03:52.620
So to illustrate this,

00:03:52.620 --> 00:03:54.270
let's take a trip to the casino

00:03:54.270 --> 00:03:57.180
to play three different games.

00:03:57.180 --> 00:04:01.200
At table number one, you
get 100 tosses of a coin.

00:04:01.200 --> 00:04:05.460
Each time you flip and it
lands on heads, you win $1.

00:04:05.460 --> 00:04:06.540
So the question is,

00:04:06.540 --> 00:04:09.960
how much would you be prepared
to pay to play this game?

00:04:09.960 --> 00:04:11.010
Well, we need to work out

00:04:11.010 --> 00:04:12.960
how much you'd expect to win in this game

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:15.600
and then pay less than
that expected value.

00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:18.780
So the probability of
throwing a head is 1/2.

00:04:18.780 --> 00:04:22.350
Multiply that by $1 and
multiply that by 100 tosses,

00:04:22.350 --> 00:04:25.050
that gives you an expected payout of $50.

00:04:25.050 --> 00:04:26.520
So you should be willing to pay

00:04:26.520 --> 00:04:29.160
anything less than $50 to play this game.

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:31.110
Sure, you might not win every time,

00:04:31.110 --> 00:04:33.750
but if you play the
game hundreds of times,

00:04:33.750 --> 00:04:35.700
the small variations
either side of the average

00:04:35.700 --> 00:04:39.090
will cancel out and you can
expect to turn a profit.

00:04:39.090 --> 00:04:41.160
One of the first people to
study this kind of problem

00:04:41.160 --> 00:04:44.190
was Abraham de Moivre in the early 1700s.

00:04:44.190 --> 00:04:46.770
He showed that if you plot the
probability of each outcome,

00:04:46.770 --> 00:04:48.480
you get a bell-shaped curve,

00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:51.690
which was later coined
the normal distribution.

00:04:51.690 --> 00:04:52.830
- Normal distributions,

00:04:52.830 --> 00:04:54.180
the traditional explanation

00:04:54.180 --> 00:04:56.970
is that when there are a lot
of effects that are random

00:04:56.970 --> 00:04:58.050
that are adding up,

00:04:58.050 --> 00:05:00.090
that's when you expect normals.

00:05:00.090 --> 00:05:03.510
So like how tall I am depends
on a lot of random things,

00:05:03.510 --> 00:05:06.300
about my nutrition, about
my parents' genetics,

00:05:06.300 --> 00:05:07.170
all kinds of things,

00:05:07.170 --> 00:05:10.650
but if these random effects are additive,

00:05:10.650 --> 00:05:14.400
that is what tends to lead to normals.

00:05:14.400 --> 00:05:17.520
- At table number two, there's
a slightly different game.

00:05:17.520 --> 00:05:20.220
You still get 100 tosses of the coin,

00:05:20.220 --> 00:05:21.053
but this time,

00:05:21.053 --> 00:05:23.850
instead of potentially
winning a dollar on each flip,

00:05:23.850 --> 00:05:26.850
your winnings are
multiplied by some factor.

00:05:26.850 --> 00:05:29.160
So you start out with $1,

00:05:29.160 --> 00:05:31.230
and then every time you toss a head,

00:05:31.230 --> 00:05:34.080
you multiply your winnings by 1.1.

00:05:34.080 --> 00:05:36.240
If instead the coin lands on tails,

00:05:36.240 --> 00:05:38.730
you multiply your winnings by 0.9.

00:05:38.730 --> 00:05:40.170
And after 100 tosses,

00:05:40.170 --> 00:05:41.760
you take home the total,

00:05:41.760 --> 00:05:43.500
that is the dollar you started with

00:05:43.500 --> 00:05:45.573
times the string of 1.1s and 0.9s.

00:05:46.770 --> 00:05:49.830
So, how much should you
pay to play this game?

00:05:49.830 --> 00:05:51.120
Well, on each flip,

00:05:51.120 --> 00:05:53.730
your payout can either grow or shrink,

00:05:53.730 --> 00:05:57.120
and each is equally likely
each time you toss the coin,

00:05:57.120 --> 00:05:59.130
so the expected factor each turn

00:05:59.130 --> 00:06:02.850
is just 1.1 plus 0.9 divided
by two, which is one.

00:06:02.850 --> 00:06:05.130
So if you start out with $1,

00:06:05.130 --> 00:06:08.190
then your expected payout is just $1.

00:06:08.190 --> 00:06:09.780
That means you should be willing to pay

00:06:09.780 --> 00:06:13.170
anything less than a dollar
to play this game, right?

00:06:13.170 --> 00:06:15.630
Well, if you look at the
distribution of payouts,

00:06:15.630 --> 00:06:17.730
you can see that you could win big.

00:06:17.730 --> 00:06:19.440
If you tossed 100 heads,

00:06:19.440 --> 00:06:21.810
you'd win 1.1 to the power of 100.

00:06:21.810 --> 00:06:24.480
That's almost $14,000,

00:06:24.480 --> 00:06:25.860
although the chance of that happening

00:06:25.860 --> 00:06:27.990
is around 1 in 10 to the power of 30.

00:06:27.990 --> 00:06:29.550
You'd be more likely to win the lottery

00:06:29.550 --> 00:06:30.870
three times in a row.

00:06:30.870 --> 00:06:34.410
On the other hand, the median
payout is around 61 cents.

00:06:34.410 --> 00:06:36.810
So if you're only
playing the game one time

00:06:36.810 --> 00:06:39.660
and you want even odds
of turning a profit,

00:06:39.660 --> 00:06:42.660
well, then you should
pay less than 61 cents.

00:06:42.660 --> 00:06:45.270
Though either way, if you played
the game hundreds of times,

00:06:45.270 --> 00:06:47.383
your payout would average out to $1.

00:06:48.330 --> 00:06:50.460
Now, watch what happens
if we switch the x-axis

00:06:50.460 --> 00:06:53.010
from a linear scale to
a logarithmic scale.

00:06:53.010 --> 00:06:54.960
Well, then you see the curve transforms

00:06:54.960 --> 00:06:56.730
into a normal distribution.

00:06:56.730 --> 00:06:58.530
That's why this type of distribution

00:06:58.530 --> 00:07:01.050
is called a log normal distribution.

00:07:01.050 --> 00:07:03.000
- When random effects multiply,

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:05.340
if I have a certain wealth

00:07:05.340 --> 00:07:08.400
and then my wealth goes up by
a certain percentage next year

00:07:08.400 --> 00:07:10.140
because of my investments,

00:07:10.140 --> 00:07:11.190
and then the year after that,

00:07:11.190 --> 00:07:14.220
it changes by another random factor,

00:07:14.220 --> 00:07:17.430
as opposed to adding, I'm
multiplying year after year.

00:07:17.430 --> 00:07:19.980
If you have a big product
of random numbers,

00:07:19.980 --> 00:07:21.630
when you take the log of a product,

00:07:21.630 --> 00:07:23.253
that's the sum of the logs.

00:07:24.180 --> 00:07:26.520
So what was a product of random numbers

00:07:26.520 --> 00:07:31.170
then gets translated into sums
of logs of random numbers,

00:07:31.170 --> 00:07:32.003
and that's what leads

00:07:32.003 --> 00:07:34.380
to this so-called log normal distribution.

00:07:34.380 --> 00:07:38.340
And log normal distributions
produce big inequalities.

00:07:38.340 --> 00:07:40.560
You don't just see a mean,

00:07:40.560 --> 00:07:42.810
you see a mean with a big long tail.

00:07:42.810 --> 00:07:45.780
It's much more likelihood
of really big events,

00:07:45.780 --> 00:07:48.750
in this case, tremendous
wealth being obtained,

00:07:48.750 --> 00:07:51.810
than you would expect from
a normal distribution.

00:07:51.810 --> 00:07:53.790
- The reason this curve is so asymmetric

00:07:53.790 --> 00:07:56.280
is because the downside is capped at zero,

00:07:56.280 --> 00:07:57.813
so at most, you could lose $1,

00:07:58.770 --> 00:08:02.733
but the upside can keep
growing up to nearly $14,000.

00:08:03.750 --> 00:08:05.730
Now let's go on to table three.

00:08:05.730 --> 00:08:07.410
Again, you'll be tossing a coin,

00:08:07.410 --> 00:08:09.570
but this time you start out with a dollar

00:08:09.570 --> 00:08:12.660
and the payout doubles
each time you toss the coin

00:08:12.660 --> 00:08:15.660
and you keep tossing
until you get a heads,

00:08:15.660 --> 00:08:17.190
then the game ends.

00:08:17.190 --> 00:08:20.610
So if you get heads on your
first toss, you get $2.

00:08:20.610 --> 00:08:22.050
If you get a tails first

00:08:22.050 --> 00:08:25.200
and then hit a heads on your
second toss, you get $4.

00:08:25.200 --> 00:08:27.120
If you flipped two tails and then a head,

00:08:27.120 --> 00:08:30.270
on your third toss,
you'd get $8, and so on.

00:08:30.270 --> 00:08:32.700
If it took you to the
nth toss to get a heads,

00:08:32.700 --> 00:08:35.430
you would get two to the n dollars.

00:08:35.430 --> 00:08:38.970
So, how much should you
pay to play this game?

00:08:38.970 --> 00:08:40.530
Well, as in our previous example,

00:08:40.530 --> 00:08:42.750
we need to work out the expected value.

00:08:42.750 --> 00:08:45.390
So suppose you throw a
head on your first try,

00:08:45.390 --> 00:08:46.710
the payout is $2

00:08:46.710 --> 00:08:49.380
and the probability of
that outcome is a half,

00:08:49.380 --> 00:08:52.770
so the expected value of
that toss is a dollar.

00:08:52.770 --> 00:08:54.990
If it takes you two tosses to get a heads,

00:08:54.990 --> 00:08:56.580
then the payout is $4

00:08:56.580 --> 00:08:59.430
and the probability of that
happening is one over four,

00:08:59.430 --> 00:09:02.280
so again, the expected value is $1.

00:09:02.280 --> 00:09:03.870
We also need to add in the chance

00:09:03.870 --> 00:09:05.550
that you flip heads on your third try,

00:09:05.550 --> 00:09:07.620
in that case, the payout is $8

00:09:07.620 --> 00:09:10.350
and the probability of that
happening is one over eight,

00:09:10.350 --> 00:09:12.283
so again, the expected value is $1.

00:09:13.530 --> 00:09:15.720
And we have to keep
repeating this calculation

00:09:15.720 --> 00:09:17.880
over all possible outcomes.

00:09:17.880 --> 00:09:20.700
We have to keep adding $1 for
each of the different options

00:09:20.700 --> 00:09:23.550
for flipping the coin, say, 10
times until it lands on heads

00:09:23.550 --> 00:09:26.010
or 100 times before you get heads.

00:09:26.010 --> 00:09:28.050
I know it's extremely unlikely,

00:09:28.050 --> 00:09:29.640
but the payout is so huge

00:09:29.640 --> 00:09:33.300
that the expected value of
that outcome is still a dollar,

00:09:33.300 --> 00:09:37.140
so it still increases the
expected value of the whole game.

00:09:37.140 --> 00:09:39.150
This means that, theoretically,

00:09:39.150 --> 00:09:43.053
the total expected value
of this game is infinite.

00:09:44.070 --> 00:09:47.220
This is known as the
St. Petersburg paradox.

00:09:47.220 --> 00:09:49.440
If you look at the
distribution of payouts,

00:09:49.440 --> 00:09:51.330
you can see it's uncapped,

00:09:51.330 --> 00:09:53.850
it spans across all orders of magnitude.

00:09:53.850 --> 00:09:56.970
You could get a payout
of $1,000, $100,000,

00:09:56.970 --> 00:09:59.190
or even a million dollars or more.

00:09:59.190 --> 00:10:01.890
And while a million
dollar payout is unlikely,

00:10:01.890 --> 00:10:03.480
it's not that unlikely,

00:10:03.480 --> 00:10:05.163
it's around one in a million.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:08.940
Now, if you transform
both axes to a log scale,

00:10:08.940 --> 00:10:12.420
you see a straight line with
a gradient of negative one.

00:10:12.420 --> 00:10:14.580
The payout of the St. Petersburg paradox

00:10:14.580 --> 00:10:16.260
follows a power law.

00:10:16.260 --> 00:10:18.090
The specific power law in this case

00:10:18.090 --> 00:10:20.190
is that the probability of a payout x

00:10:20.190 --> 00:10:24.330
is equal to x to the power of
negative one or one over x.

00:10:24.330 --> 00:10:26.760
In the previous games when
you have a normal distribution

00:10:26.760 --> 00:10:28.740
or even a log normal distribution,

00:10:28.740 --> 00:10:31.140
you can measure the width
of that distribution,

00:10:31.140 --> 00:10:32.970
its standard deviation.

00:10:32.970 --> 00:10:34.380
And in a normal distribution,

00:10:34.380 --> 00:10:37.590
95% of the data fall within
two standard deviations

00:10:37.590 --> 00:10:38.670
from the mean.

00:10:38.670 --> 00:10:41.820
But with a power law, like in
the St. Petersburg paradox,

00:10:41.820 --> 00:10:43.950
there is no measurable width,

00:10:43.950 --> 00:10:46.890
the standard deviation is infinite.

00:10:46.890 --> 00:10:50.130
This makes power laws a
fundamentally different beast

00:10:50.130 --> 00:10:52.770
with some very weird properties.

00:10:52.770 --> 00:10:54.810
- Imagine you take a
bunch of random samples

00:10:54.810 --> 00:10:55.980
and then average them

00:10:55.980 --> 00:10:58.590
and then take more random
samples and average them,

00:10:58.590 --> 00:11:01.470
you'll find that the
average keeps going up,

00:11:01.470 --> 00:11:03.240
it doesn't converge.

00:11:03.240 --> 00:11:04.320
And the more you measure,

00:11:04.320 --> 00:11:06.900
the bigger the average is,

00:11:06.900 --> 00:11:09.390
which is really weird,
it sounds impossible,

00:11:09.390 --> 00:11:12.150
but it's because it has such a heavy tail,

00:11:12.150 --> 00:11:15.480
meaning the probability of
really whopping big events

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:18.360
is so significant that
if you keep measuring,

00:11:18.360 --> 00:11:19.530
occasionally you're gonna measure

00:11:19.530 --> 00:11:21.420
one of those extreme outliers

00:11:21.420 --> 00:11:24.780
and they will totally skew the average.

00:11:24.780 --> 00:11:26.460
It's sort of like saying,

00:11:26.460 --> 00:11:30.240
if you're standing in a room
with Bill Gates or Elon Musk,

00:11:30.240 --> 00:11:32.820
the average wealth in that room

00:11:32.820 --> 00:11:36.960
is gonna be 100 billion
dollars or something (laughs)

00:11:36.960 --> 00:11:39.990
because the average is
dominated by one outlier.

00:11:39.990 --> 00:11:43.140
- And that same idea, one
outlier can dominate the average,

