00:18:38.130 --> 00:18:39.570
Right at the phase transition,

00:18:39.570 --> 00:18:41.217
you get fractal behavior

00:18:41.217 --> 00:18:43.440
and that pops out as a power law.

00:18:43.440 --> 00:18:45.600
- In fact, whenever you find a power law,

00:18:45.600 --> 00:18:47.550
that indicates you're
dealing with a system

00:18:47.550 --> 00:18:49.950
that has no intrinsic scale,

00:18:49.950 --> 00:18:53.430
and that is a signature of a
system in a critical state,

00:18:53.430 --> 00:18:56.940
which turns out has huge consequences.

00:18:56.940 --> 00:18:59.460
- See, normally in a magnet
below the Curie temperature,

00:18:59.460 --> 00:19:01.890
each atom influences only its neighbors.

00:19:01.890 --> 00:19:04.050
If one atom's magnetic moment flips up,

00:19:04.050 --> 00:19:06.390
then that means that its
neighbors are slightly more likely

00:19:06.390 --> 00:19:07.740
to point up too.

00:19:07.740 --> 00:19:09.120
But that influence is local,

00:19:09.120 --> 00:19:11.040
it dies out just a few atoms away.

00:19:11.040 --> 00:19:13.560
But as the magnet approaches
its critical temperature,

00:19:13.560 --> 00:19:16.170
those local influences
start to chain together.

00:19:16.170 --> 00:19:17.790
One spin nudges its neighbor

00:19:17.790 --> 00:19:20.400
and that neighbor nudges
the next and so on,

00:19:20.400 --> 00:19:22.860
like a rumor spreading through a crowd.

00:19:22.860 --> 00:19:25.380
And the result is that the
effective range of influence

00:19:25.380 --> 00:19:26.490
keeps expanding,

00:19:26.490 --> 00:19:28.230
