00:22:54.360 --> 00:22:55.980
then the forest gets too thick

00:22:55.980 --> 00:23:00.270
and then it's ripe for
this sort of massive fire.

00:23:00.270 --> 00:23:01.103
- For a magnet,

00:23:01.103 --> 00:23:03.750
you have to painstakingly
tune it to the critical point,

00:23:03.750 --> 00:23:06.720
but the forest naturally
drives itself there.

00:23:06.720 --> 00:23:10.080
This phenomenon is called
self-organized criticality.

00:23:10.080 --> 00:23:11.370
Yeah, and if you let it run,

00:23:11.370 --> 00:23:15.180
what you get is, again,
a power law distribution.

00:23:15.180 --> 00:23:16.890
So this is log-log,

00:23:16.890 --> 00:23:18.630
so it should be a straight line.

00:23:18.630 --> 00:23:22.050
- That kind of stuff
seems so totally random

00:23:22.050 --> 00:23:23.037
and unpredictable,

00:23:23.037 --> 00:23:25.050
and it is in one way,

00:23:25.050 --> 00:23:26.640
and yet it follows a pattern.

00:23:26.640 --> 00:23:28.650
There's a consistent mathematical pattern

00:23:28.650 --> 00:23:30.393
to all these kind of disasters.

00:23:31.445 --> 00:23:33.300
It's shocking.

00:23:33.300 --> 00:23:36.210
- Is there something fractal about this?

00:23:36.210 --> 00:23:39.810
- Mostly in terms of the, I
guess, domains of the trees

00:23:39.810 --> 00:23:42.240
when you're at that critical state.

00:23:42.240 --> 00:23:45.750
So you get very dense areas,
you get non-dense areas.

00:23:45.750 --> 00:23:48.360
And as a result, when a
single lightning bolt strikes,

00:23:48.360 --> 00:23:50.610
you can get fires of all sizes.

00:23:50.610 --> 00:23:54.210
Most often you get small fires
of 10 or fewer trees burning.

00:23:54.210 --> 00:23:55.500
A little less frequently,

00:23:55.500 --> 00:23:57.660
you get fires of less than 100 trees.

00:23:57.660 --> 00:23:59.430
And then every once in a while,

00:23:59.430 --> 00:24:01.200
you get these massive fires

00:24:01.200 --> 00:24:04.140
that reverberate throughout
the entire system.

00:24:04.140 --> 00:24:06.810
Now, you might expect that
because the fire is so large,

00:24:06.810 --> 00:24:09.660
there has to be a
significant event causing it,

00:24:09.660 --> 00:24:11.190
but that's not the case

00:24:11.190 --> 00:24:13.920
because the cause for each
fire is the exact same,

00:24:13.920 --> 00:24:16.080
it's a single lightning strike.

00:24:16.080 --> 00:24:18.360
The only difference is where it strikes

00:24:18.360 --> 00:24:21.180
and the exact makeup of
the forest at that time.

00:24:21.180 --> 00:24:23.310
So in some very real way,

00:24:23.310 --> 00:24:24.930
the large fires are nothing more

00:24:24.930 --> 00:24:27.300
than magnified versions of the small ones,

00:24:27.300 --> 00:24:29.610
and even worse, they're inevitable.

00:24:29.610 --> 00:24:30.630
So what we've learned

00:24:30.630 --> 00:24:32.700
is that for systems in a critical state,

00:24:32.700 --> 00:24:35.550
there are no special events
causing the massive fires.

00:24:35.550 --> 00:24:39.000
There was nothing special
about the Yellowstone fire.

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:41.730
- In 1935, the US Forest
Service established

00:24:41.730 --> 00:24:44.040
the so-called 10:00 AM policy.

00:24:44.040 --> 00:24:46.140
The plan was to suppress every single fire

00:24:46.140 --> 00:24:49.620
by 10:00 AM on the day
following its initial report.

00:24:49.620 --> 00:24:52.170
Now, naively, this strategy makes sense.

00:24:52.170 --> 00:24:54.840
I mean, if you keep all
fires under strict control,

00:24:54.840 --> 00:24:57.240
then none can ever get out of hand.

00:24:57.240 --> 00:25:00.573
But it turns out this
strategy is extremely risky.

00:25:01.470 --> 00:25:04.050
- So let's say we're gonna bring down

00:25:04.050 --> 00:25:05.730
the lightning probability,

00:25:05.730 --> 00:25:06.930
so it's very small,

00:25:06.930 --> 00:25:08.880
only one in a million right now,

00:25:08.880 --> 00:25:12.780
and we're also gonna crank up
the tree growth a little bit.

00:25:12.780 --> 00:25:14.910
Now what do you think is gonna happen?

00:25:14.910 --> 00:25:17.460
- We're gonna get some big
fires, I would imagine,

00:25:17.460 --> 00:25:21.660
like a lot of not fire
and then some huge fires.

00:25:21.660 --> 00:25:22.986
Yeah.

00:25:22.986 --> 00:25:25.110
(Derek laughs)

00:25:25.110 --> 00:25:26.100
- [Casper] Yep.

00:25:26.100 --> 00:25:27.240
- Oh boy.

00:25:27.240 --> 00:25:28.073
- [Casper] So nowadays,

00:25:28.073 --> 00:25:30.330
the fire service has a
very different approach.

00:25:30.330 --> 00:25:32.520
They acknowledge that
some fires are essential

00:25:32.520 --> 00:25:34.830
to make the megafires less likely.

00:25:34.830 --> 00:25:36.720
So they let most small fires burn

00:25:36.720 --> 00:25:39.030
and only intervene when necessary.

00:25:39.030 --> 00:25:42.180
In some cases, they even
intentionally create small fires

00:25:42.180 --> 00:25:44.220
to burn through some of the buildup,

00:25:44.220 --> 00:25:45.360
though it could take years

00:25:45.360 --> 00:25:47.190
to return the forest to its natural state

00:25:47.190 --> 00:25:49.860
after a century of fire suppression.

00:25:49.860 --> 00:25:51.720
But it's more than just
the Earth's forests

00:25:51.720 --> 00:25:53.770
that are balanced in this critical state.

00:25:54.900 --> 00:25:56.970
Every day, the Earth's crust is moving

00:25:56.970 --> 00:25:58.290
and rearranging itself.

00:25:58.290 --> 00:25:59.730
Stresses build up slowly

00:25:59.730 --> 00:26:02.280
as tectonic plates rub against each other.

00:26:02.280 --> 00:26:04.830
Most of the time, you get
a few rocks crumbling,

00:26:04.830 --> 00:26:07.740
the ground might move just
a fraction of a millimeter,

00:26:07.740 --> 00:26:09.960
but the stresses dissipate
in many earthquakes

00:26:09.960 --> 00:26:11.790
that you wouldn't even feel.

00:26:11.790 --> 00:26:13.260
- There are really tiny earthquakes

00:26:13.260 --> 00:26:16.620
that are happening right
now beneath your feet,

00:26:16.620 --> 00:26:19.350
you just can't feel 'em
because they're very small.

00:26:19.350 --> 00:26:20.460
But they are earthquakes,

00:26:20.460 --> 00:26:23.610
they're driven by small slipping movements

00:26:23.610 --> 00:26:25.020
in the Earth's crust.

00:26:25.020 --> 00:26:27.180
- [Casper] But sometimes
those random movements

00:26:27.180 --> 00:26:30.540
can trigger a powerful chain reaction.

00:26:30.540 --> 00:26:31.560
- [Derek] In Kobe, Japan,

00:26:31.560 --> 00:26:35.340
the morning of January 17, 1995
seemed just like any other.

00:26:35.340 --> 00:26:36.690
This was a peaceful city,

00:26:36.690 --> 00:26:38.220
and although Japan as a country

00:26:38.220 --> 00:26:39.720
is no stranger to earthquakes,

00:26:39.720 --> 00:26:42.630
Kobe hadn't suffered a
major quake for centuries.

00:26:42.630 --> 00:26:43.650
Generations grew up

00:26:43.650 --> 00:26:46.560
believing the ground
beneath them was stable,

00:26:46.560 --> 00:26:48.390
but that morning, deep underground,

00:26:48.390 --> 00:26:51.960
a stress released nearby
the Nojima fault line.

00:26:51.960 --> 00:26:54.630
The stress propagated to the
next section of the fault

00:26:54.630 --> 00:26:55.560
and the next.

00:26:55.560 --> 00:26:56.430
Within seconds,

00:26:56.430 --> 00:26:59.460
the ruptured cascaded along
40 kilometers of crust,

00:26:59.460 --> 00:27:01.530
shifting the ground by up to two meters

00:27:01.530 --> 00:27:03.120
and releasing the energy equivalent

00:27:03.120 --> 00:27:05.130
of numerous atomic bombs.

00:27:05.130 --> 00:27:07.590
The resulting quake
destroyed thousands of homes

00:27:07.590 --> 00:27:09.030
along with most major roads

00:27:09.030 --> 00:27:10.830
and railways leading into the city.

00:27:10.830 --> 00:27:12.780
It killed over 6,000 people

00:27:12.780 --> 00:27:15.513
and forced 300,000 from their homes.

00:27:16.380 --> 00:27:19.230
- How far it goes depends a lot on chance

00:27:19.230 --> 00:27:22.260
and the organization of
all that stress field

00:27:22.260 --> 00:27:23.430
in the Earth's crust.

00:27:23.430 --> 00:27:26.340
And it just seems to be
organized in such a way

00:27:26.340 --> 00:27:28.680
that it is possible oftentimes

00:27:28.680 --> 00:27:31.350
for the earthquake to
trickle along an avalanche

00:27:31.350 --> 00:27:32.850
along a long way

00:27:32.850 --> 00:27:35.370
and produce a very large
unusual earthquake.

00:27:35.370 --> 00:27:37.980
But if you look at the process
behind that earthquake,

00:27:37.980 --> 00:27:40.830
it is exactly the same physical process.

00:27:40.830 --> 00:27:43.200
It's just that the
earthquake-generating process

00:27:43.200 --> 00:27:45.000
naturally produces events

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:47.760
that range over an
enormous range of scale,

00:27:47.760 --> 00:27:50.010
and we're not really used
to thinking about that.

00:27:50.010 --> 00:27:51.750
- We have this ingrained assumption

00:27:51.750 --> 00:27:54.390
that we can use the past
to predict the future,

00:27:54.390 --> 00:27:56.040
but when it comes to earthquakes

00:27:56.040 --> 00:27:58.740
or any system that's in a critical state,

00:27:58.740 --> 00:28:00.870
that assumption can be catastrophic

00:28:00.870 --> 00:28:02.940
because they're famously unpredictable.

00:28:02.940 --> 00:28:05.190
So, how can you even
begin to model something

00:28:05.190 --> 00:28:07.440
like the behavior of earthquakes?

00:28:07.440 --> 00:28:09.960
- [Derek] In 1987,
