00:34:07.230 --> 00:34:08.880
and the thing that's spreading-

00:34:08.880 --> 00:34:09.900
- Is disease.

00:34:09.900 --> 00:34:12.390
- Is disease, yeah.

00:34:12.390 --> 00:34:15.030
- You almost get something for nothing

00:34:15.030 --> 00:34:16.560
at these critical points.

00:34:16.560 --> 00:34:18.840
- See, many of these systems
fall into what's known

00:34:18.840 --> 00:34:20.490
as universality classes.

00:34:20.490 --> 00:34:22.560
Some of them you need
to tune to get there,

00:34:22.560 --> 00:34:24.420
like magnets at their Curie temperature

00:34:24.420 --> 00:34:27.180
or fluids like water or carbon dioxide

00:34:27.180 --> 00:34:28.440
at their critical point,

00:34:28.440 --> 00:34:29.790
but some other systems

00:34:29.790 --> 00:34:32.220
seem to organize
themselves to criticality,

00:34:32.220 --> 00:34:36.000
like the forest fires or
sandpiles or earthquakes.

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:38.280
But what's crazy is that if you succeed

00:34:38.280 --> 00:34:41.100
in understanding just
one system from a class,

00:34:41.100 --> 00:34:44.670
then you know how all the
systems in that class behave,

00:34:44.670 --> 00:34:48.210
and that includes even the
crudest simplest toy models,

00:34:48.210 --> 00:34:50.220
like the simulations we've looked at.

00:34:50.220 --> 00:34:53.310
So you can model
incredibly complex systems

00:34:53.310 --> 00:34:55.320
with the most basic of models.

00:34:55.320 --> 00:34:57.540
And some people think
this critical thinking

00:34:57.540 --> 00:34:59.160
applies even further.

00:34:59.160 --> 00:35:00.570
When we look around the world,

00:35:00.570 --> 00:35:01.950
there are lots of systems

00:35:01.950 --> 00:35:03.750
that show the same power law behavior

00:35:03.750 --> 00:35:05.760
that we see in this critical systems.

00:35:05.760 --> 00:35:08.040
It's in everything from DNA sequencing

00:35:08.040 --> 00:35:10.950
to the distribution of
species in an ecosystem

00:35:10.950 --> 00:35:13.920
to the size of mass
extinctions throughout history.

00:35:13.920 --> 00:35:16.560
We even see the same
behavior in human systems,

00:35:16.560 --> 00:35:18.270
like the populations of cities,

00:35:18.270 --> 00:35:20.220
fluctuations in stock prices,

00:35:20.220 --> 00:35:22.260
citations of scientific papers,

00:35:22.260 --> 00:35:25.340
and even the number of deaths in wars.

00:35:25.340 --> 00:35:27.900
So some people argue that these systems

00:35:27.900 --> 00:35:31.440
and perhaps many parts of our
world also organize themselves

00:35:31.440 --> 00:35:33.000
to this critical point.

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:35.370
- So the fact that all
these natural hazards,

00:35:35.370 --> 00:35:36.203
as they call them,

00:35:36.203 --> 00:35:38.220
floods, wildfires, and earthquakes,

00:35:38.220 --> 00:35:40.440
they all follow power law distributions

00:35:40.440 --> 00:35:45.060
means that these extreme
events are much more common

00:35:45.060 --> 00:35:48.180
than you would think based on
