be persistent than consistent.

00:40:07.020 --> 00:40:08.820
- [Derek] Though as we saw
in the second coin game,

00:40:08.820 --> 00:40:10.800
totally random multiplicative returns

00:40:10.800 --> 00:40:14.280
give you a log normal
distribution, not a power law.

00:40:14.280 --> 00:40:15.150
To get a power law,

00:40:15.150 --> 00:40:17.673
there must be some
other mechanism at play.

00:40:18.810 --> 00:40:19.950
In the early 2000s,

00:40:19.950 --> 00:40:22.650
Albert-Lszl Barabsi
was studying the internet,

00:40:22.650 --> 00:40:23.610
and to his surprise,

00:40:23.610 --> 00:40:26.130
he found that there was no normal webpage

00:40:26.130 --> 00:40:28.170
with some average number of links.

00:40:28.170 --> 00:40:30.720
Instead, the distribution
followed a power law.

00:40:30.720 --> 00:40:32.190
A few sites like Yahoo

00:40:32.190 --> 00:40:34.410
had thousands of times more connections

00:40:34.410 --> 00:40:36.030
than most of the others.

00:40:36.030 --> 00:40:38.250
Barabasi wondered what could be causing

00:40:38.250 --> 00:40:39.900
this power law of the internet,

00:40:39.900 --> 00:40:41.610
so he made a simple prediction.

00:40:41.610 --> 00:40:43.860
As new sites were added to the internet,

00:40:43.860 --> 00:40:46.890
they were more likely to
link to well-known pages.

00:40:46.890 --> 00:40:48.060
To test this prediction,

00:40:48.060 --> 00:40:51.570
he and his colleague Rka Albert 
ran a simulation.

00:40:51.570 --> 00:40:53.910
They started with a
network of just a few nodes

00:40:53.910 --> 00:40:56.550
and gradually they added
new nodes to the network

00:40:56.550 --> 00:40:59.130
with each new node more
likely to connect to those

00:40:59.130 --> 00:41:00.450
with the most links.

00:41:00.450 --> 00:41:03.420
As the network grew, a power law emerged.

00:41:03.420 --> 00:41:05.190
The power was around negative two,

00:41:05.190 --> 00:41:08.910
which almost exactly matched
the real data of the internet.

00:41:08.910 --> 00:41:11.040
